pros:
- Very structured, process-oriented company - if you like that kind of environment, you can thrive;
- Fast-growing, fast-paced, and open to innovation - I've seen few ideas be outright rejected by the organization, but you're on your own to bring them to life on top of your daily responsibilities;
- Tiny discount on some Amazon purchases.

cons:
- Content is misunderstood, even by senior leadership, as asset production - real understanding of content marketing is lacking;
- A LOT of process for process sake, which mean you'll work without a purpose/clear business objective most of the time just to check boxes;
- You'll work really hard, and get no recognition for it;
- Amazon hires people who during the interview process are perceived to be 50% better than those performing the job. That means you'll most likely be hired at the wrong level, and perform above it for years until you can clear a promotion - no matter what you do;
- NO work-life balance (Bezo's opinion on it is clear, believe it!)

pros:
- Stable Payroll;
- Company has great perspective;
- Stock keep growing;
- You will work with the biggest companies as your customers;
- Free access to some of learning resources(acloudguru, linux academy, etc..);
- Phone compensation up to 50$ / month;
- Uber/Lyft compensation up to 170$ / month;

cons:
- Noisy oncall;
- Promotion process in weird. It doesn't matter what you did and how, but how many people you showed your face;
- Internal tools are terrible. You will have to rely on not reliable toolbox. 99% Availability for internal services? Not even close;
- Managers and engineers all tries to push new service to get promotion. As result a lot of services doing basically the same thing and lack of integration between them;
- Leadership principles is something works only for interviews and promotion process. Once you join you will not see any of these in your collegues; People are too tied doing firefighing every day.

pros:
-Interesting projects;
- attention to new ideas;
- smart people around;
- access to greatest and latest tech;
- a lot of interesting data;
- easy to experiment with new ideas;
- some managers are really great;
- lots of trainings and resources for development;
- easy to understand the culture based on Leadership Principles;

cons:
- no lunch, drinks, snacks;
- somewhat, vertical structure in decision making;
- generally, lack of collaboration across teams/groups;
- benefits below market (you pay more than half of total insurance cost, 401k is only partially matched after 2years);
- if training is beyond the scope of project then they are not allowed.
